    id: "minimum-depth-binary-tree",
    title: "Minimum Depth of Binary Tree",
    category: "trees",
    difficulty: "easy",
    description: "Find minimum depth from root to nearest leaf node.",
    constraints: "1 <= n <= 10^5",
    techniques: ["binary-search-tree"],
    examples: [{"input":"7\n1 2 3 4 5 6 7","output":"2","explanation":"Root 1 has leaf children 2 and 3, min depth=2"}],
    test_cases: [{"input":"7\n1 2 3 4 5 6 7","expected":"2"},{"input":"3\n1 -1 2","expected":"2"}],
    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <algorithm>\n#include <climits>\nusing namespace std;\n\nstruct TreeNode {\n  int val;\n  TreeNode *left, *right;\n  TreeNode(int v) : val(v), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n};\n\nint minDepth(TreeNode* root) {\n  if (!root) return 0;\n  if (!root->left && !root->right) return 1;\n  int l = root->left ? minDepth(root->left) : INT_MAX;\n  int r = root->right ? minDepth(root->right) : INT_MAX;\n  return 1 + min(l, r);\n}\n\nint main() {\n  int n; cin >> n;\n  int vals[n];\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> vals[i];\n  TreeNode* nodes[n];\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) nodes[i] = new TreeNode(vals[i]);\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n    if (2*i+1 < n && vals[2*i+1] != -1) nodes[i]->left = nodes[2*i+1];\n    if (2*i+2 < n && vals[2*i+2] != -1) nodes[i]->right = nodes[2*i+2];\n  }\n  cout << minDepth(nodes[0]) << endl;\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nmin-depth:\n       1\n      / \\\n     2   3\n    / \\\n   4   5\n\n  minDepth(1):\n    left=minDepth(2): left=minDepth(4)=1, right=minDepth(5)=1 → min=1, return 2\n    right=minDepth(3): leaf → return 1\n    min(2,1)=1, return 1+1=2\n\n  Result: 2 (path 1→3)\n\n  Skewed tree:\n    1\n     \\\n      2\n       \\\n        3\n  minDepth(1): left=null(INT_MAX), right=3 → return 3\n```\nRecursive: if node is leaf, return 1. Otherwise return 1 + min(minDepth(left) if left exists else INF, minDepth(right) if right exists else INF). For a skewed tree, returns height. Time O(n), Space O(h).",
