    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nstruct TreeNode {\n  int val;\n  TreeNode *left, *right;\n  TreeNode(int v) : val(v), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n};\n\nint main() {\n  int n, target; cin >> n;\n  int vals[n];\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> vals[i];\n  TreeNode* nodes[n];\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) nodes[i] = new TreeNode(vals[i]);\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n    if (2*i+1 < n && vals[2*i+1] != -1) nodes[i]->left = nodes[2*i+1];\n    if (2*i+2 < n && vals[2*i+2] != -1) nodes[i]->right = nodes[2*i+2];\n  }\n  cin >> target;\n\n  // BFS, find target, output next in queue\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nlevel-order-successor:\n       1\n      / \\\n     2   3\n    / \\ / \\\n   4  5 6  7\n\n  BFS order: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7\n\n  Target=5:\n  Queue states:\n  [1] → pop 1, push 2,3\n  [2,3] → pop 2, push 4,5\n  [3,4,5] → pop 3, push 6,7\n  [4,5,6,7] → pop 4\n  [5,6,7] → pop 5 == target → next in queue = 6 → output 6\n\n  Target=7: last in level order → no successor → -1\n```\nStandard BFS. When we pop a node that matches the target, the next node in the queue is the level-order successor. Time O(n), Space O(n).",
